1.description: Attempted to use the IMU when it wasn't initialised. *

2.description: Attempted to issue an IMU_CMD_NONE to the IMU module.

3.description: There was an error in the EventManager that is preventing the IMU component operating.

7.description: Cannot issue a new command to the IMU since the IMU is not in the WAIT_NEW_COMMAND state. It could either not be initialised or is still finishing another command

8.description: There was an error in the I2C driver.  See the corresponding value of DP.IMU.I2C_ERROR for the root cause.

9.description: Unexpected value of an I2c_ActionStatus return.

10.description: The maximum number of events has been reached and no more events will be raised until an event is polled.

11.description: There was insufficient memory to increase the size of the event  lists.

12.description: A call to realloc() failed while trying to shrink the lists. This indicates memory corruption.

13.description: An EventManager function was called when the EventManager wasn't initialised. Make sure to call EventManager_init() before using the EventManager.

14.description: A config file update was attempted with a config file that has an invalid CRC.

15.description: An error occured in the EEPROM driver.

16.description: Indicates an error occured in the event manager which is being propagated.

17.description: All stored configuration files are corrupted.

18.description: Error indicating that recovery action required by the EEPROM initialisation failed.  From the Tivaware user manual section 9.2.3.8 if this error occurs in a stable power state this is an indicator that the EEPROM has exceeded its lifetime of write/erases. If the supply voltage is unstable when this error occurs the operation may still succeed once the voltage is stabilised.

19.description: Indicates that the maximum number of wait attempts on the EEPROM peripheral being enabled has been exceeded.

20.description: The EEPROM self test failed because the size returned by the Tivaware function EEPROMSizeGet() and the expected size EEPROM_SIZE_BYTES differ.

21.description: The EEPROM status is either EEPROM_RC_WORKING or EEPROM_RC_WRBUSY, meaning that a write operation cannot be done until the EEPROM is no longer busy.

22.description: A write operation cannot succeed because the user has no permission to write to the address (EEPROM_RC_NOPERM).

23.description: An EEPROM write failed because the combintion of address and length would exceed the size of the EEPROM.

24.description: An EEPROM read failed because the combintion of address and length would exceed the size of the EEPROM.

25.description: Inputs to an EEPROM function must be word-aligned, but some inputs wern't.

26.description: The I2C driver has not been initialised.

27.description: Failed to enable an I2C peripheral.

28.description: Failed to enable a GPIO peripheral. *

29.description: Indicates that no action has been queued for the given device

30.description: Attempted to check the TivaWare error status of an action which is of type NONE.

31.description: Error indicating that a user attempted to read recieved bytes from a device that had sent data.

32.description: Attempted to get the recieved bytes from a non successful action. Use I2c_get_device_action_status to check that the action was successful before calling I2c_get_device_recved_bytes.

34.description: Failed to allocate memory for send action.

35.description: Failed to allocate memory for recieve action.

36.description: A new action could not be queued as the maximum number of actions has been reached.

37.description: A new action could not be queued as the maximum number of actions has been reached.

38.description: An unexpected action step index was found while executing an action.

39.description: An unexpected action step index was found while executing an action.

40.description: A master I2C module is busy.

41.description: Failed to acknowledge the address of an I2C device, is the device address correct?

42.description: Failed to acknowledge data sent to the master. The slave could be unresponsive.

43.description: The arbitration of the bus has been lost. This could indicate that a slave is in error.

44.description: An unkown TivaWare library error has occured

46.description: The action cannot be queued as the module (bus) the device is on is already locked by another device.

47.description: The GPIO peripheral failed to enable.

48.description: The GPIO mode was neither GPIO_MODE_INPUT or GPIO_MODE_OUTPUT

49.description: The GPIO id number was greater than the total number of GPIOs

50.description: An action was attempted on the GPIO when it has not been initialised.

1.description: New command event.  This event is raised when a new command is issued by a user to the Imu module. It is used to identify when a new command is available to be executed. The user should not raise this event themselves, instead use the Imu_new_command() function.

2.description: IMU gyroscope read command completed successfully.

4.description: IMU magnetometer read command completed successfully.

6.description: IMU temeprature read command completed successfully.

8.description: Event used to signal a state change in the IMU. This is done so that the new state will run it's first function in the next cycle without the system going to sleep.

11.description: Event associated with an event manager error.  This event indicates that an error has occured in the EventManager, and the corresponding error code in the EventManager's DataPool DP.EVENTMANAGER.ERROR_CODE has been set.  Note, if the error arises from already being at the maximum number of events the error code will be set and the corresponding DP.EVENTMANAGER.MAX_EVENTS_REACHED flag will be raised. This event will not be raised.

12.description: Event indicating that a config file update succeeded.

13.description: Event indicating that a config file update failed.  Check DP.MEMSTOREMANAGER.ERROR_CODE for an error code.

14.description: Event indicating that a corrupted config file was found while loading from the EEPROM.  Check DP.MEMSTOREMANAGER.CFG_FILE_x_OK flags to determine which file was corrupted.

15.description: This event indicates that a new action has been requested for the I2C driver to execute.

16.description: Event that indicates when an I2C action has been finished. The user must use I2c_get_device_action_status for their device to determine whether or not their action has finished, or if it was another action.  This event __shall not__ be polled by the user, instead EventManager_is_event_raised must be used. The I2c module will clear the event when all finished actions have been handled.
